# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# agenthook environment
#
# Copy this file to `.env` and place it BESIDE your agenthook.config.json (the
# loader auto-loads a .env from the config's directory and from your cwd). It
# backs the ${VAR} references in that config, e.g. "token": "${ASANA_TOKEN}".
#
#   cp .env.example .env   &&   $EDITOR .env
#
# Rules of thumb:
#   • Shell-exported vars win over values here (good for CI / secret managers).
#   • Uncomment ONLY the block for the tracker you chose in agenthook.config.json.
#   • This file is gitignored — never commit a filled-in .env.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TRACKER  (must match tracker.type in agenthook.config.json)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ── Asana ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Personal Access Token. Create at https://app.asana.com/0/my-apps
# Format: 2/<userGid>/<secret>  (one long string, no spaces)
# Config: tracker: { "type": "asana", "token": "${ASANA_TOKEN}", ... }
#
# ASANA_TOKEN=2/1199xxxxxxxxxxxx/abcdef0123456789abcdef0123456789


# ── Jira Cloud ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The API token is the ONLY Jira secret (https://id.atlassian.com/manage-profile/security/api-tokens).
# site/email/projectKey are plain values in agenthook.config.json (email = the Basic-auth
# username, not a secret). The webhook signing secret is GENERATED + stored by agenthook and
# printed on `start` to paste into the Jira webhook; the assignee accountId is derived from
# /myself. So neither needs an env var.
# Config: tracker: { "type":"jira", "site":"<X>", "email":"bot@yourco.com", "token":"${JIRA_API_TOKEN}", ... }
#
# JIRA_API_TOKEN=ATATT3xFfGF0xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#
# Jira webhooks are created by hand in Jira admin (token-based REST creation is Connect-only),
# so the URL can't rotate — pair Jira with a STABLE ingress (ngrok 'domain' or hosted).


# ── GitHub Issues ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# A Personal Access Token is the ONLY GitHub secret. Classic: scopes `repo` +
# `admin:repo_hook`. Fine-grained (scoped to the repo): Issues RW + Webhooks RW + Metadata R.
# The pipeline runs off issue LABELS; the webhook is auto-created + signed with a secret
# agenthook generates. The assignee login is derived from /user. See docs/github-setup.md.
# Config: tracker: { "type":"github", "repository":"owner/name", "token":"${GITHUB_TOKEN}", ... }
#
# GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# INGRESS  — only if ingress.type = "ngrok" in agenthook.config.json
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# USUALLY NOT NEEDED: if you use the ngrok binary it self-auths from its own
# config (`ngrok config add-authtoken <token>`), so omit ingress.authtoken entirely.
# Only set this on a headless/CI host where ngrok isn't pre-configured — then add
# ingress.authtoken: "${NGROK_AUTHTOKEN}" to the config and fill it here.
# Token: https://dashboard.ngrok.com/get-started/your-authtoken
#
# NGROK_AUTHTOKEN=2xXxXxXxXxXxXxXxXxXxXxXxXxX_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#
# A hosted/static ingress (ingress.type = "hosted") needs NO env var — its public
# URL is set directly in the config: ingress: { "type": "hosted", "url": "https://hook.you.com" }
